Who else will you be celebrating this Pride? 🏳️‍🌈 Lauren Morelli and Samira Wiley: According to @JessicaOOTC, @lomorelli and @samirawiley are “the cutest wives ever.” Writing for Orange Is the New Black sparked Lauren’s journey to self-acceptance and love with Samira. Ruth Ellis: Living to the age of 101, Ruth was known as the oldest lesbian ever. She came out in 1915 and was accepted by her family. She spent her life with Babe, who she met in the 1920s. Their Detroit home was known as “The Gay Spot,” a refuge for queer teens. Sylvia Rivera: Another important figure in the Stonewall Riots, was lesbian icon Sylvia Rivera. LGBTQ+ activists at the time acknowledged her as a role model for young Puerto Rican transgender people. Stormé DeLarverie: Known as the “gay Rosa Parks,” Stormé was arrested the night of the Stonewall Rebellion. Marsha P. Johnson: Famous for her involvement at Stonewall, Marsha was a pioneer and queen. Fueled by her joie de vivre, Marsha’s intersectional identity and activism inspired the first Pride parades. Magnus Hirschfeld: A German physician and sexologist who advocated for homosexual and transgender rights. Studying homosexual subcultures, he developed a system that identified a spectrum of sexuality that intersects with gender. Alicia Garza: As one of the co-creators of Black Lives Matter, @aliciagarza is on the frontlines fighting for all Black lives, including those of intersectional identities. Jonathan Van Ness: All hail @jvn whose style, humor, and gender-queer identity celebrates and empowers so many to embrace their true selves through radical self acceptance. Dolores del Rio: Known as Hollywood’s Latina Lady Lover, this crossover actress’ career spanned over 5 decades. She was a member of “The Sewing Circle," a group of Hollywood bisexuals and lesbians who met regularly for lunch and love connections. Sophia Jex Blake and Margaret Todd: This 1800s power couple were known as “doctor wives.” Not only did the two break barriers in science and mathematics—they were also in a long term relationship well before gay marriage was legal or accepted. From doctor wives to a gender-queer grooming expert, @JessicaOOTC breaks down 10 LGBTQ+ People You Should Know.
